scipy reference — quantum-trade numerical kernels
=================================================

scipy_reference.txt holds reference outputs for three exactly-reproducible
numerical kernels in the 13503 quantum-vs-classical trade engine, computed by an
independent third-party authority and used to externally validate Kshana's own
implementations (see tests/scipy_reference.rs). These files are not part of the
Kshana source and are not shipped in the published crates/packages.

Oracle
------
scipy 1.17.1 — the canonical scientific-computing library (Virtanen et al.,
"SciPy 1.0: fundamental algorithms for scientific computing in Python", Nature
Methods 17, 2020; open source, BSD). Three kernels are checked, the same way DOP
is validated against gnss_lib_py and the ML metrics against scikit-learn:

  NNLS     qparams_from_adev_curve   ->  scipy.optimize.nnls
           (the measured-ADEV ingestion: a non-negative least-squares fit of an
            Allan-deviation curve to the {1/tau, tau, tau^3} holdover-noise basis)
  CHI2     detection::chi2_inv_cdf   ->  scipy.stats.chi2.ppf
           (the filter-consistency NEES/NIS chi-square confidence bands; the
            Wilson-Hilferty quantile is checked at the operating pooled dof >= 8,
            where it is tight — sub-0.1% by dof ~100, effectively exact in the
            thousands the UKF pools to)
  VANLOAN  clock_state van-Loan Q    ->  scipy.linalg.expm  (Van Loan 1978)
           (the discrete clock process-noise / holdover-coast covariance, the
            computational spine of the trade table's holdover times)

Scope (honest): these validate the trade engine's *computational kernels* — the
ADEV fit, the consistency bands, the holdover covariance. They do NOT validate
the device-performance numbers (clock/CAI parameters), which quantify a partner's
hardware and stay MODELLED (no device, no validation — by the work package's own
design). See src/verification.rs.

Provenance / reproducibility
----------------------------
Generated by the committed generate_scipy_reference.py (scipy 1.17.1 + numpy,
Python 3.11). All real-valued inputs/outputs use Python repr so the Rust test
parses identical f64. The van-Loan discrete Q is computed by the standard
Van Loan (1978) matrix-exponential algorithm on the 3-state clock model
F = [[0,1,0],[0,0,1],[0,0,0]], Qc = diag(q_wf, q_rw, q_drift); the analytic
closed form Kshana uses integrates to the same matrix.

Format
------
'#'-prefixed comments, then one line per case:
  NNLS    <name> | <taus,> | <adevs,> | <q_wf> <q_rw> <q_drift>
  CHI2    <p> <dof> <value>
  VANLOAN <name> <q_wf> <q_rw> <q_drift> <dt> | <q00> <q01> <q02> <q11> <q12> <q22>
